Student Performance Data Set

https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/student+performance

Citation:

P. Cortez and A. Silva. Using Data Mining to Predict Secondary School Student Performance. In A. Brito and J. Teixeira Eds.,Proceedings of 5th FUture BUsiness TEChnology Conference (FUBUTEC 2008) pp. 5-12, Porto, Portugal, April, 2008, EUROSIS, ISBN 978-9077381-39-7.

\(\color{blue}{\text{Data set information}}\)

This data approach student achievement in secondary education of two Portuguese schools.

The data attributes include student grades, demographic, social and school related features) and it was collected by using school reports and questionnaires.

Two data sets are provided regarding the performance in two distinct subjects: Mathematics (mat) and Portuguese language (por).

\(\color{blue}{\text{Variables information:}}\)

  1. school - student’s school (binary: ‘GP’ - Gabriel Pereira or ‘MS’ - Mousinho da Silveira)

  2. sex - student’s sex (binary: ‘F’ - female or ‘M’ - male)

  3. age - student’s age (numeric: from 15 to 22)

  4. address - student’s home address type (binary: ‘U’ - urban or ‘R’ - rural)

  5. famsize - family size (binary: ‘LE3’ - less or equal to 3 or ‘GT3’ - greater than 3)

  6. Pstatus - parent’s cohabitation status (binary: ‘T’ - living together or ‘A’ - apart)

  7. Medu - mother’s education (numeric: 0 - none, 1 - “primary education (4th grade)”, 2 - “ 5th to 9th grade“, 3 - “secondary education” or 4 - “ higher education")

  8. Fedu - father’s education (numeric: 0 - none, 1 - primary education (4th grade), 2 - “ 5th to 9th grade“, 3 - “ secondary education” or 4 - “ higher education")

  9. Mjob - mother’s job (nominal: ‘teacher’, ‘health’ care related, civil ‘services’ (e.g. administrative or police), ‘at_home’ or ‘other’)

  10. Fjob - father’s job (nominal: ‘teacher’, ‘health’ care related, civil ‘services’ (e.g. administrative or police), ‘at_home’ or ‘other’)

  11. reason - reason to choose this school (nominal: close to ‘home’, school ‘reputation’, ‘course’ preference or ‘other’)

  12. guardian - student’s guardian (nominal: ‘mother’, ‘father’ or ‘other’)

  13. traveltime - home to school travel time (numeric: 1 - less than 15 min., 2 - 15 to 30 min., 3 - 30 min. to 1 hour, or 4 - more than 1 hour)

  14. studytime - weekly study time (numeric: 1 - less than 2 hours, 2 - 2 to 5 hours, 3 - 5 to 10 hours, or 4 - more than 10 hours)

  15. failures - number of past class failures (numeric: n if between 1 and 3 , else 4)

  16. schoolsup - extra educational support (binary: yes or no)

  17. famsup - family educational support (binary: yes or no)

  18. paid - extra paid classes within the course subject (Math or Portuguese) (binary: yes or no)

  19. activities - extra-curricular activities (binary: yes or no)

  20. nursery - attended nursery school (binary: yes or no)

  21. higher - wants to take higher education (binary: yes or no)

  22. internet - Internet access at home (binary: yes or no)

  23. romantic - with a romantic relationship (binary: yes or no)

  24. famrel - quality of family relationships (numeric: from 1 - very bad to 5 - excellent)

  25. freetime - free time after school (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)

  26. goout - going out with friends (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)

  27. Dalc - workday alcohol consumption (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)

  28. Walc - weekend alcohol consumption (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)

  29. health - current health status (numeric: from 1 - very bad to 5 - very good)

  30. absences - number of school absences (numeric: from 0 to 93)

  31. G1 - first period grade (numeric: from 0 to 20)

  32. G2 - second period grade (numeric: from 0 to 20)

  33. G3 - final grade (numeric: from 0 to 20, output target)

\(\color{red}{\text{Important note:}}\)

For the purpose of learning (also because it’s more unique), I decided not to use all the variables. I chose the ones that picked my curiosity. I don’t know what the result will be, so fingers crossed for a good one.

Paper source for more details: http://www3.dsi.uminho.pt/pcortez/student.pdf

From the paper provided above I know that:

  1. G1 and G2 have a strong correlation to G3. This occurs because G3 is the final year grade (issued at the 3rd period), while G1 and G2 correspond to the 1st and 2nd period grades.

  2. The data can be used for regression, multiclassification or classification.

I will use the data for classification (Pass/Fail)

I will not use all the variables, only:

  • famsize - family size (binary: ‘LE3’ - less or equal to 3 or ‘GT3’ - greater than 3)

  • Pstatus - parent’s cohabitation status (binary: ‘T’ - living together or ‘A’ - apart)

  • Medu - mother’s education (numeric: 0 - none, 1 - “primary education (4th grade)”, 2 - “ 5th to 9th grade“, 3 - “secondary education” or 4 - “ higher education")

  • Fedu - father’s education (numeric: 0 - none, 1 - primary education (4th grade), 2 - “ 5th to 9th grade“, 3 - “ secondary education” or 4 - “ higher education")

  • Mjob - mother’s job (nominal: ‘teacher’, ‘health’ care related, civil ‘services’ (e.g. administrative or police), ‘at_home’ or ‘other’)

  • Fjob - father’s job (nominal: ‘teacher’, ‘health’ care related, civil ‘services’ (e.g. administrative or police), ‘at_home’ or ‘other’)

  • guardian - student’s guardian (nominal: ‘mother’, ‘father’ or ‘other’)

  • famsup - family educational support (binary: yes or no)

  • higher - wants to take higher education (binary: yes or no)

  • internet - Internet access at home (binary: yes or no)

  • Dalc - workday alcohol consumption (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)

  • Walc - weekend alcohol consumption (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)

  • absences - number of school absences (numeric: from 0 to 93)

  • G3 - final grade (numeric: from 0 to 20, output target), which i will convert into Passed > 10; Failed < 11

Perform Chi-square test goodness-of-fit and check the critical value

  • HO: There is no significant difference in distribution between the groups that Failed or Passed

  • Ha: There is a significant difference in distribution between the groups that Failed or Passed 

# number of samples
N = length(df$G3)
print(paste0("Number of samples: ", N))
## [1] "Number of samples: 395"
# test 
chisq.test(table(df$G3), correct = F)
## 
##  Chi-squared test for given probabilities
## 
## data:  table(df$G3)
## X-squared = 1.3392, df = 1, p-value = 0.2472
# critical value
print(paste0("Critical value: ", qchisq(.95, chisq.test(table(df$G3), correct = F)$parameter)))
## [1] "Critical value: 3.84145882069412"

Looks like both the p-value an the critical value indicate that we can accept H0: X-squared(1, N = 395) = 1.34, p = 0.25

Maening that there is no significant difference in distribution between the groups that Failed or Passed.

  • Check distribution (Chi-S. goodness of fit) and plot.

  • Perform Test of independence against G3 (Chi-Squared test of Ind. or Fisher exact test)

A few helper functions

Function to perform Chi-Squared goodness of fit test

goodness_test <- function(df_var){
  result <- chisq.test(table(df_var), correct = F)
  # test info
  df <- result$parameter
  st <- round(result$statistic, digits = 3)
  n <- length(df_var)
  p <- round(result$p.value, digits = 3)
  
  # print test results
  print(result)
  print(paste0("Result: (df = ", df,", N=", n, ") = ", st, "; p = ", p))
  # print critical value
  print(paste0("Critical value: ",round(qchisq(.95, df), 3)))
}

Function to plot one categorical variable

distribution_plot_1 <- function(df, var, var_name){
  ggplot(df, aes(x = {{var}})) + geom_bar(fill="lightblue") +
  ggtitle(paste0(var_name, " Distribution Plot"))
}

Function to plot two categorical variables

distribution_plot_2 <- function(df, IV, DV, IV_name, DV_name){
  ggplot(df, aes(x = {{IV}}, fill = {{DV}})) +
  geom_bar(position = "dodge") +
  scale_fill_brewer() +
  ggtitle(paste0(IV_name, " and ", DV_name))
}

Function to test for independence (CHI-SQUARED TEST OF INDEPENDANCE)

  • H0: Variables are independent

  • Ha: Variables are dependent

ind_chi <- function(IV, DV){
  result <- chisq.test(table(DV, IV))
  df <- result$parameter
  st <- result$statistic
  n <- length(DV)
  p <- round(result$p.value, digits = 3)
  to_print <- paste0("(",df,", N=", n, ") = ", st, "; p = ", p)
  
  print(table(DV, IV))
  cat("\n")
  print(result)
  cat("\n")
  print(to_print)
}

Density plot

ggplot(df, aes(absences, group = G3, fill = G3))+
  geom_density(alpha = 0.4)

Performing a Independent sample T-test:

  • H0: The mean of absences of the group that failed does not differ from the mean of
    absences of the group that passed

  • Ha: The mean of absences of the group that failed is differ significantly from the mean of
    absences of the group that passed.

ASSUMPTIONS:

    1. DV (absences) is continuous
    1. IV (G3) has two independent groups, “Passed” and “Failed”
    1. The groups in G3 should have similar sample size (this has been already checked above)
    1. “G3” in each group should be normally distributed. T-test is resistant if this assumption is broken
    1. Groups in “activities” should have similar variance (perform Levene’s test)

Checking variance

  • H0: Variances are equal

  • Ha: variances are not equal

leveneTest(absences ~ G3, df)
## Levene's Test for Homogeneity of Variance (center = median)
##        Df F value Pr(>F)
## group   1  2.4917 0.1152
##       393

Levene’s test give us a p-value of 0.11 so we can accept H0. Meaning that there is no significant difference between the variances.

T-test

t.test(absences ~ G3, df, var.equal = T)
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  absences by G3
## t = 1.1233, df = 393, p-value = 0.262
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group Falied and group Passed is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.6796396  2.4913904
## sample estimates:
## mean in group Falied mean in group Passed 
##             6.188172             5.282297
# calculate the critical value
crit_result <- qt(0.95, 393, lower.tail = T)
print(paste0("Critical Value: ", crit_result))
## [1] "Critical Value: 1.64874011363683"
# out of curiousity I will check the effect siez
coh_effect <- cohensD(absences ~ G3, df, method = "pooled")
print(paste0("Effect: ", coh_effect))
## [1] "Effect: 0.11322821521104"

T-test RESULTS:

  • T-est results: t(393)=1.12; p=0.26

  • Critical value: 1.65

  • Effect: 0.11 (very small)

Based on the information above we can accept H0. Meaning that the mean of absences of the group that failed does not differ from the mean of absences of the group that passed

Check assumption:

  1. Homogeneity of Variance assumption

Plot

plot(anova_, 1)

Looks like there are a few values (277, 184, 75) which can affect normality and homogeneity of variance. Before removing the outliers I will perform Levene’s test as well.

leveneTest(absences ~ Medu, df)
## Levene's Test for Homogeneity of Variance (center = median)
##        Df F value   Pr(>F)   
## group   4  3.5115 0.007844 **
##       390                    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

The p-value (0.009) is less than the significant value. This is an indication that there is significant difference in variance between groups.

  1. Normality assumption

Plot

plot(anova_, 2)

We can observe a deviation of the points from the line in the right tail.

# get residuals
anova_residuals <- residuals(object = anova_)

# check normality (Shapiro-Wilk test)
shapiro.test(anova_residuals)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  anova_residuals
## W = 0.71592, p-value < 2.2e-16

The p-value (0.001) is less than the significant value. Indicating that the distribution is not normal

Since the assumptions are not met I will perform a non-parametric test (Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test)

kruskal.test(absences ~ Medu, df)
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  absences by Medu
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 7.5884, df = 4, p-value = 0.1079

The Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test gives us a p-value of 0.11. Meaning that there are no significant difference in means between the groups.

Checking for overdispersion

There are 2 ways to check for overdispersion:

1st method

If the ratio is a lot larger than 1, than we can assume that there is an overdispersion issue

deviance(fit_2)/df.residual(fit_2)
## [1] 1.343848

We got a result of 1.34 which is slightly higher than 1, meaning that there is a very small chance that we have the issue with overdispersion.

2nd method

Check if there is a significant difference between 2 models, binomial() and quacibinomial()

Building a model with the argument family = quasibinomial()

fit_2_quasi <- glm(G3 ~ Mjob + higher, df, family = quasibinomial())
pchisq(summary(fit_2_quasi)$dispersion * fit_2$df.residual, fit_2$df.residual, lower = F)
## [1] 0.3410127

With a p-values of 0.34 (not significant) can conclude that the model doesn’t have an overdispersion issue.
